=== Ferroelectric and dielectric ===

Materials are only ferroelectric below their corresponding transition temperature {{math|''T''<sub>0</sub>}}.<ref name=Myers404>{{harvnb|Myers|1997|pp=404–05}}</ref> Ferroelectric materials are all [[pyroelectric|pyroelectric]] and therefore have a spontaneous electric polarisation as the structures are unsymmetrical.

Ferroelectric materials' polarization is subject to [[hysteresis|hysteresis]] (Figure 4); that is they are dependent on their past state as well as their current state. As an electric field is applied the dipoles are forced to align and polarisation is created, when the electric field is removed polarisation remains. The hysteresis loop depends on temperature and as a result as the temperature is increased and reaches {{math|''T''<sub>0</sub>}} the two curves become one curve as shown in the dielectric polarisation (Figure 5).<ref name=Pascoe1>{{harvnb|Pascoe|1973|pp=190–91}}</ref>

=== 相对介电常数  ===

A modified version of the Curie–Weiss law applies to the dielectric constant, also known as the [[relative_permittivity|relative permittivity]]:<ref name=Webster/><ref>{{harvnb|Webster|1999|pp=6.55–6.56}}</ref>

:<math>\epsilon = \epsilon_0 + \frac{C}{T-T_\mathrm{0}}.</math>

==应用==
A heat-induced ferromagnetic-paramagnetic transition is used in [[magneto-optical|magneto-optical]] storage media, for erasing and writing of new data. Famous examples include the [[Sony|Sony]] [[Minidisc|Minidisc]] format, as well as the now-obsolete [[CD-RW#CD-MO|CD-MO]] format. Curie point electro-magnets have been proposed and tested for actuation mechanisms in passive safety systems of [[Breeder_reactor|fast breeder reactors]], where [[Control_rod|control rods]] are dropped into the reactor core if the actuation mechanism heats up beyond the material's curie point.<ref name="Takamatsu">{{cite journal |last1=Takamatsu |title=Demonstration of Control Rod Holding Stability of the Self Actuated Shutdown System in Joyo for Enhancement of Fast Reactor Inherent Safety |journal=Journal of Nuclear Science and Technology |volume=44 |issue=3 |url=https://doi.org/10.1080/18811248.2007.9711316}}</ref> Other uses include temperature control in [[soldering_iron|soldering iron]]s,<ref>{{harvnb|TMT-9000S}}</ref> and stabilizing the magnetic field of [[tachometer|tachometer]] generators against temperature variation.<ref>{{harvnb|Pallàs-Areny|Webster|2001|pp=262–63}}</ref>
